Summary: Classifying bad loans with Lending Club loan data¶

The data are obtained from Kaggle. The data can also be downloaded from the Lending Club website. My objective is to classify whether a loan will become bad (i.e. late payments, charged off or defaulted) based on a borrower's personal characteristics. In this notebook,

  1. Data preparation
    • I first check and transform the data to gather all the necessary predictors. There are nearly 150 indicators in the data set. Based on the descriptions, I select about 20 variables that I think can help to distinguish the bad loans from the good ones. These variables reflect, for example, the annual incomes, overall debts, purposes of borrowing, places of residence, etc.
  1. Exploratory data analysis
    • Then, I do extensive exploratory data analyses that involve data visualization with matplotlib, seaborn and plotly
  1. Classification models
    • For the classification of bad loans: I compare the performances of the models: Support Vector Machine, Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Random Forest, AdaBoost with Decision Tree, Adaboost with Random Forest, and Extreme Gradient Boosting library XGBoost. Most models perform well, with high accuracy and recall scores.

       '8 years','n/a'], data=[10,6,4,0.5,2,9,5,3,7,1,8,0])

#        'Does not meet the credit policy. Status:Charged Off']
df['loan_type']=df['loan_status'].replace('Does not meet the credit policy. Status:Fully Paid','Fully Paid')\
                                    .apply(lambda x: 'Bad' if x not in ['Current','Fully Paid'] else x)
df['ratio_int_pymnt']=df['total_rec_int']/df['total_pymnt']

def Cat_Plot(df, x, y, ax):
    by_x = pd.crosstab(df[y], df[x], normalize='index')*100
    by_x.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax)
    ax.set_ylabel('% of all loans by {}'.format(x))
    ax.legend(loc=[1.05,0])
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=0)
    
def Bar_Plot(df, x, y, estimator, ax, xlabel):
    sns.barplot(ax=ax, data=df, x=x, y=y, estimator=estimator)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    
def Violin_Plot(df, x, y, ax, xlabel):
    sns.violinplot(ax=ax, data=df, x=x, y=y)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    
def Box_Plot(df, x, y, ax, xlabel):
    sns.boxplot(ax=ax, data=df, x=x, y=y)
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel)
    
def Scatter_Plot(df, x, y, hue, ax):
    sns.scatterplot(ax=ax, data=df, x=x, y=y, hue=hue)

def Map_Plot(df, GeoVar, ValVar, title, unit):
    fig = go.Figure(data=go.Choropleth(
        locations=df[GeoVar],
        z=df[ValVar].astype(float),
        locationmode='USA-states',
        colorscale='Blues',
        autocolorscale=False,
        text=df[GeoVar].astype('str')+'<br>'+df[ValVar].astype('str')+' '+unit,
        marker_line_color='white', # line markers between states
        colorbar_title=unit
    ))
    
    fig.update_layout(
        title_text=title,
        geo = dict(
            scope='usa',
            projection=go.layout.geo.Projection(type = 'albers usa'),
            showlakes=True, # lakes
            lakecolor='rgb(255, 255, 255)'),
    )
    return fig

bystate=df['loan_amnt'].groupby(df.addr_state).sum().reset_index()

def features_plot(ax, mod, l_names, title):
    if 'feature_importances_' in mod.__dir__():
        feature_weights=pd.Series(mod.feature_importances_, index=l_names).sort_values(ascending=False)
    else:
        feature_weights=pd.Series(mod.coef_[0], index=l_names).sort_values(ascending=False)
    sns.barplot(ax=ax, x=feature_weights.values, y=feature_weights.index).set_title(title)

def scores_plot(models, X, y, title, ax):
    scores=[accuracy_score(y, models[mod].predict(X)) for mod in models.keys()]
    sns.barplot(ax=ax, x=scores, y=list(models.keys())).set_title(title)
    print(title,scores)

scores_plot(models, X_neg, y_neg, 'Recall scores: Good (repaid) loans', ax[1])

Plotting ROC curves¶

In [21]:
def ROC_plot(classifier, cv, X, y, graph_title, ax):
    for i, (train, test) in enumerate(cv.split(X, y)):
        classifier.fit(X[train], y[train])
        plot_roc_curve(classifier, X[test], y[test],
                             name='ROC fold {}'.format(i),
                             alpha=0.5, lw=1, ax=ax)
    
    ax.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--', lw=2, color='r',
            label='Chance', alpha=.8)
    
    ax.set(xlim=[-0.05, 1.05], ylim=[-0.05, 1.05],
           title="Receiver operating characteristic {}".format(graph_title))
    ax.legend(loc="lower right")
    
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)

fig, ax=plt.subplots(4,2,figsize=(10,24))
for i, mod in enumerate(models.keys()):
    ROC_plot(models[mod], cv, X, y, mod, ax[i//2,i%2])
fig.delaxes(ax[3,1])
fig.show()

Cross-validation - Recall scores: Bad loans vs. Good loans¶

In [22]:
X=np.array(df_sub[~df.loan_type.isin(['Current'])][l_cat+l_cont].fillna(0))
y=np.array(df_sub[~df_sub.loan_type.isin(['Current'])]['loan_type']=='Bad')

print('% of bad loans: {}'.format(np.nansum(y)/len(y)*100))

scores_positive=pd.DataFrame(index=range(5), columns=models.keys())
scores_negative=pd.DataFrame(index=range(5), columns=models.keys())

strkfold=StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
j=0
for i_train, i_test in strkfold.split(X,y):
    X_train, y_train = X[i_train,:], y[i_train]
    X_test, y_test = X[i_test,:], y[i_test]
    
    for mod in models.keys():
        models[mod].fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    X_pos=X_test[y_test>0,:]
    y_pos=y_test[y_test>0]
    X_neg=X_test[y_test==0,:]
    y_neg=y_test[y_test==0]
    
    scores_positive.loc[j]=[accuracy_score(y_pos, models[mod].predict(X_pos)) for mod in models.keys()]
    scores_negative.loc[j]=[accuracy_score(y_neg, models[mod].predict(X_neg)) for mod in models.keys()]
    j+=1

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
plt.errorbar(x=scores_positive.columns.values, y=scores_positive.mean(), yerr=scores_positive.std(), fmt='o')
fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
plt.errorbar(x=scores_negative.columns.values, y=scores_negative.mean(), yerr=scores_negative.std(), fmt='o')
fig.axes[0].set_title('Recall scores: Bad loans')
fig.axes[1].set_title('Recall scores: Good (repaid) loans')
plt.show()

Check if we can predict which bad loan will default or get charged off:¶

This is just to try and see if we can differentiate the late payments from the defaulted or charged-off loans. The loans with late payments may eventually default or get charged off. Thus, these borrowers may not be that different from one another. The low performances of the classification models seem to confirm that the predictors do not distinguish well the two classes.
